				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Puerto Rico&#8217;s Second Cut to Junk Debt</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Mary Williams Walsh			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-02-07T19:44:30+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">February 7, 2014 2:44 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">February 7, 2014 2:44 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/07/business/dealbook/dbpix-debt/dbpix-debt-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/07/business/dealbook/dbpix-debt/dbpix-debt-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/07/business/dealbook/dbpix-debt/dbpix-debt-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002695447" width="592" height="395" alt="A pedestrian walks past the shelter of a homeless person on the steps of an abandoned building in Ponce, Puerto Rico."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A pedestrian walks past the shelter of a homeless person on the steps of an abandoned building in Ponce, Puerto Rico.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Alvin Baez/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/07/moodys-joins-s-p-in-cutting-puerto-rico-to-junk/" data-title="Puerto Rico&#8217;s Second Cut to Junk Debt" data-description="The new downgrade was expected to further narrow the islandâs room for tight financial maneuvering and has reportedly given rise to discussions with lenders about short-term relief on certain payments.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><br />
<span id="t19h35m" class="update">Updated, 7:35 p.m. | </span><a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/moodys_corporation/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Moody's Investors Service.">Moodyâs Investors Service</a> downgraded Puerto Ricoâs general-obligation debt to junk status on Friday, intensifying a cash squeeze on the island and prompting some residents to blame hard-nosed creditors for their mounting troubles.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was Puerto Ricoâs second downgrade to junk this week after <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/standard_and_poors/index.html?inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More articles about Standard &#038; Poor's.">Standard &#038; Poorâs</a> <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/04/s-p-lowers-puerto-rico-debt-to-junk-status/" title="About the move.">took the same step</a> on Tuesday. Though not unexpected, the new downgrade was expected to further narrow the islandâs room for tight financial maneuvering and has reportedly given rise to discussions with lenders about short-term relief on certain payments.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âMany times, the creditors will show flexibility because they donât want to bring the issuer to its knees,â said Robert Donahue of Municipal Market Advisors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A number of Puerto Ricoâs outstanding financial commitments contain promises to make big cash payments quickly if two of the three main ratings agencies cut its credit to junk, which has now taken place.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The payments, estimated at as much as $940 million, are supposed to secure the outstanding commitments, but if they soak up all of Puerto Ricoâs available cash, they would destabilize the islandâs shaky finances, possibly sending it into a self-feeding downward spiral. Market participants said they were closely watching the Puerto Rican governmentâs response to the downgrades.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThey need to articulate a plan,â said Laurence Gottlieb, chairman of Fundamental Advisors, a firm that invests in distressed government debt.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Puerto Ricoâs treasury secretary, Melba Acosta Febo, and the chairman of its Government Development Bank, David H. Chafey Jr., issued a joint statement on Friday, saying: âWe strongly disagree with <a href="//dealbook.on.nytimes.com/public/overview?symbol=MCO&#038;inline=nyt-org" class="tickerized" title="More information about Moody's Corporation">Moodyâs</a> decision, and we will not relent in our plans to strengthen our fiscal situation. We remain confident that we have the liquidity on hand to satisfy all liquidity needs until the end of the fiscal year, including any cash needs resulting from recent rating agency actions.â The fiscal year ends June 30.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The two top financial officials also said they were in talks with lenders they did not identify about easing the islandâs liquidity squeeze, either by extending the payment schedules of existing debt or taking on new debt.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/08/business/Debt/Debt-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/08/business/Debt/Debt-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/08/business/Debt/Debt-blog480.jpg" id="100000002696278" width="480" height="320" alt="The downgrade was expected to further narrow the islandâs room for tight financial maneuvering."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="320"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The downgrade was expected to further narrow the islandâs room for tight financial maneuvering.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Alvin Baez/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Puerto Ricoâs financial affairs have an outsize effect on the rest of the United States because its debt is unusually widely held. Its debt is popular because it pays tax-exempt interest in all 50 states, thanks to Puerto Ricoâs legal status. Many investors hold the debt without knowing it because tax-exempt <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/your-money/investments/mutual-funds-and-etfs/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about mutual funds and exchange-traded funds.">mutual funds</a> often include it in their portfolios. There have been concerns that mutual funds might have to dump their Puerto Rican debt after a downgrade or that individual investors might flee.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One large mutual fund company that holds Puerto Rican debt, OppenheimerFunds, said in a statement on Friday that the downgrade did not activate any selling rules, even in cases where its funds had limits on noninvestment-grade holdings. It said it was required to adhere to those portfolio limits at the time it bought bonds but not if they were downgraded later.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Moodyâs said many years of deficit spending and underfunding of public pensions had taken a heavy toll on the island, leaving it with a high debt burden and scarce available cash.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âIn our view, the commonwealthâs credit profile is no longer consistent with investment-grade characteristics,â Moodyâs said in its announcement that it had cut Puerto Ricoâs general-obligation rating two notches, to Ba2 from Baa3. It said that it was keeping a negative outlook, indicating that more downgrades were possible.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Moodyâs acknowledged steps the Puerto Rican government had taken to strengthen its finances, like cutting back on certain pensions for government workers, reining in government spending, issuing less debt and promoting economic development.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWhile some economic indicators point to a preliminary stabilization, we do not see evidence of economic growth sufficient to reverse the commonwealthâs negative financial trends,â Moodyâs said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Moodyâs also downgraded the outstanding debt issued by the Sales Tax Financing Corporation, the islandâs independent borrowing authority, although those debts remain in the investment-grade range. The corporation, known by its Spanish acronym Cofina, was established in 2006 to help Puerto Rico borrow during a previous downturn. Its bonds are backstopped by a special dedicated sales tax and are considered more secure than bonds backed by general revenue.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Cofina had already exhausted its existing borrowing capacity, but officials in Puerto Rico had hoped to add new capacity this year so that it could bring new bonds to market in the next few weeks. With its higher rating, Cofina was expected to be able to borrow at a lower cost.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The downgrades have led to a change of plans, Mr. Donahue said. Instead of using Cofina to sell debt to the <a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/m/municipal_bonds/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier" class="tickerized" title="More articles about municipal bonds.">municipal bond</a> market, Puerto Rico is expected to issue up to $2 billion of general-obligation bonds, selling them to other institutions, like hedge funds or sovereign wealth funds. Puerto Ricoâs constitution has an unusual provision that elevates general-obligation debt above all other obligations, even payments for essential services to its residents.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe trick is going to be, what kind of security are they going to pledge without diminishing the security of the existing bondholders and without further damaging the potential for economic growth?â Mr. Donahue said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Puerto Rico has been borrowing just to fill holes in its budget in recent years and is approaching its legal debt limit. It would use up its remaining capacity if it succeeds with the planned $2 billion offering this spring. After that, it would have to balance its budget with painful tax and fee increases or cuts in public services, which could cause an outcry in a commonwealth that has already suffered through years of recession and service cuts.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe question at the bottom of all of this is whether the economy can withstand this,â Mr. Donahue said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Soon after the downgrade by S.&#038;P. on Tuesday, Gov. Alejandro Garcia Padilla introduced a seven-point plan of more budget cuts, higher taxes, infrastructure investments and negotiations with creditors, among other measures.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThroughout this all, they have continued to show good will,â Mr. Donahue said of Puerto Ricoâs officials. âItâs just going to be increasingly difficult for him to show good faith to bondholders and at the same time show the people in Puerto Rico that heâs on their side.â</p>
